The lack of an equivalent of <i>offsetof</i> in C++ is a real pity. This effectively prohibits using C-style data containers, whereby container's control data is embedded into the data instance itself. This sort of thing:<p><pre><code>  struct record
  {
    int foo;
    int bar;
    ...

    list_item item; // keeps 'record' on some list
    tree_item item; // keeps 'record' on some tree
  };
</code></pre>
There's no concise and memory-efficient way of doing the same in C++.

This is my preferred method for Python (faux-)switches:<p><pre><code>  cuil_buzz = {
      1: 'All the rage!',
      2: 'Worst product e-v-e-r.',
      3: ' ... '
  }.get(day, None)</code></pre>
